00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:31.640
Yeah, absolutely. So the first one, I think, is the one that's probably hardest to wrap our heads

00:09:31.640 --> 00:09:37.320
around. And it's that speaking is habitual, not natural. Because we are born, potentially,

00:09:37.320 --> 00:09:43.159
with the ability to speak. And that isn't true for everyone. But for most of us, it is. We think

00:09:43.159 --> 00:09:49.239
that speaking is something that we can just do. But public speaking and being a good and effective

00:09:49.239 --> 00:09:53.640
communicator is habitual, which means that it can be learned, that there are a set of skills

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:59.559
that you can start to incorporate into your life to become better at doing that. And so for those

00:09:59.559 --> 00:10:04.760
of you who say, oh, I'm not a good speaker, or I don't like public speaking, it is something that

00:10:04.760 --> 00:10:10.200
there is a future for. And I think that's really important, right? That you don't have to stop

00:10:10.200 --> 00:10:15.080
and not do it just because you're not good at it. At this moment, you can become good at it.

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:21.799
And that's exciting, I think. The second one is speaking is embodied. And

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:27.000
maybe this is a no-brainer, but we thought it was really important to call out. Because we

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:33.000
talked to a lot of people who are saying to us, well, I ran it in my head. And let me tell you,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.880
I've done plays where I did nothing but run the lines in my head for days and days and days. And

00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:42.520
then the first time they came out of my mouth, I stumbled and fell flat, and it didn't go well.

00:10:43.479 --> 00:10:48.359
That's my biggest example of learning lots of words. But if we're doing it in our head,

00:10:48.359 --> 00:10:53.559
we're not actually putting all the pieces and parts together, because speaking is embodied.

00:10:53.559 --> 00:10:58.200
There is a muscle memory to it. So when the words come out of our mouth and we stand on our two feet

00:10:58.200 --> 00:11:03.799
or however we're going to present those words out loud, we start to learn something new about

00:11:03.799 --> 00:11:10.359
the words that we're actually sharing. So that's something to consider if you're like, I was running

00:11:10.359 --> 00:11:15.479
it in my head. I knew it really well five minutes ago. Maybe say it out loud and see what changes.

