00:40:50.199 --> 00:40:58.840
the web to something linear is a messy process. And there isn't going to be one tried and true,

00:40:58.840 --> 00:41:07.080
I can always do it this way to make it work. It's accepting that. And that's why this is one of the

00:41:07.080 --> 00:41:14.280
problematic threshold concepts for people because you can't remove the mess. There was actually a

00:41:14.280 --> 00:41:20.520
speaker this year at Pasa. And this person on the first call came and they'd done the homework,

00:41:20.520 --> 00:41:25.479
they'd worked really hard, I could tell on their talk and what they wanted to share. And it was

00:41:25.479 --> 00:41:30.439
really well organized, it was clearly articulated. And then the questions they started getting that

00:41:30.439 --> 00:41:37.800
from the audience was really showing them that the audience wasn't that interested in that topic.

00:41:38.600 --> 00:41:45.080
And it threw them so far off, like, I could just see this person on their face, like, almost going

00:41:45.080 --> 00:41:50.760
white, like, what am I going to do? And, you know, I wish I would have been an even better coach in

00:41:50.760 --> 00:41:56.280
that moment, because I wish I could have told this person, it's okay, what you're feeling right now,

00:41:56.280 --> 00:42:01.800
this is the first call, this is the time to know this, and to feel this, you're not at the end.

00:42:03.560 --> 00:42:06.600
So I don't know if I'm fully answering what you're talking about, Grace, except to,

00:42:06.600 --> 00:42:11.879
you at one point said, how do I remove the mess? And the idea of this threshold concept is you can't.

00:42:12.439 --> 00:42:17.639
No. You have, part of it is accepting the mess and breathing through it and also knowing you're

00:42:17.639 --> 00:42:24.600
not alone. This is just part of speaking. And one more point, Grace, because it sounds like

00:42:24.600 --> 00:42:32.120
you might be a native French speaker. I'm an Arabic speaker, but I also speak French.

00:42:32.120 --> 00:42:38.439
Arabic, okay, Arabic. That is not one that my ear is well trained on. So the other thing is that

00:42:38.439 --> 00:42:42.840
people will give a lot of grace to people who are speaking English, as I think you've seen

00:42:42.840 --> 00:42:47.159
in the comments. People will give a lot of grace to people who are not speaking their

00:42:47.159 --> 00:42:53.320
native language to give a presentation, and you should accept that grace. Yeah, thanks. Thank you.

00:42:53.959 --> 00:43:01.320
Thank you. I saw, okay, we have a lot of awesome questions coming in here. I know we have

00:43:01.959 --> 00:43:07.239
a little under 20 minutes, but I wanted to make sure I got to, Marlene, you just,

00:43:07.239 --> 00:43:11.639
you had asked a question a few minutes ago about like the pace of speech. Do you want to jump in?

00:43:14.199 --> 00:43:21.719
Yeah. So when I get really excited about what I'm talking about or nervous, either of those two,

00:43:22.679 --> 00:43:31.000
my speaking speed goes off the rails. I mean, so fast, almost like my words become one long word.

00:43:32.840 --> 00:43:36.919
It's something that I've worked hard on over the last decade, and I still struggle with it,

00:43:36.919 --> 00:43:43.320
but I wanted to get some tips or thoughts you have about that, either what you do maybe when

00:43:43.320 --> 00:43:49.800
you catch yourself in the middle of a presentation starting to speed up, or if you're just going quick

00:43:49.800 --> 00:43:53.639
out the gate because you're worried about time constraints, any tips you have would be helpful

00:43:53.639 --> 00:44:03.159
there. Hi, Marlene. I'm also sometimes an excited fast talker, so I can feel you. I'll give you all

00:44:03.159 --> 00:44:07.560
like an app actually we've been playing with that you could try out if you wanted to. It's an app

00:44:07.560 --> 00:44:15.000
called SpeakOh. Can you put it in the chat for me, Blythe? This is, it's a new like AI-ish kind

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:20.199
of tool, but it gives you metrics. So if you wanted to try and measure your voice, first of

00:44:20.199 --> 00:44:25.320
all, I would question whether it's your internal barometer that's telling you it's too fast or

00:44:25.320 --> 00:44:29.879
whether externally it's too fast, and these kind of apps can actually help you to determine.

00:44:30.840 --> 00:44:36.679
A good rate of speech is somewhere between 125 to 160-ish words per minute.

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:43.800
Some people can listen faster than that, like people who listen to all their podcasts twice,

00:44:43.879 --> 00:44:48.520
and two times speed, which I think Blythe does. I can't do that. I'm not a good listener that way,

00:44:49.800 --> 00:44:55.560
but what allows us to listen even at faster speeds, so if you catch yourself, Marlene,

00:44:55.560 --> 00:45:01.159
talking really fast or anybody else on the call, what you want to do is lean into pauses and

00:45:01.159 --> 00:45:07.320
breaths. So when you think about newscasters, they actually speak at an incredibly fast rate of

00:45:07.320 --> 00:45:14.439
speech, but we understand them because they put in pauses and they put in breaths, and we think of

00:45:14.439 --> 00:45:20.679
those as auditory punctuation. If I were to put text in front of you and remove the periods and

00:45:20.679 --> 00:45:26.439
the commas and the, um, any sort of punctuation, it would be very difficult to read. Same with

00:45:26.439 --> 00:45:31.800
speaking. We need the punctuation as listeners. So lean into breathing, lean into pausing.

00:45:32.760 --> 00:45:38.120
Now there was a subset of what you said, which is one is I get going to excited, I go going fast

00:45:38.120 --> 00:45:44.360
with them excited, and the other is I have so much to say and so little time. And if you're in the,

00:45:44.360 --> 00:45:50.120
if anyone's in the I have so much to say and so little time bucket, I'm here to tell you that

00:45:50.120 --> 00:45:56.439
there is going to be a boxing match always between time and content. Time gets to win.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:01.719
So if you are rushing because you have so much to say, you actually need to look at your content

00:46:01.719 --> 00:46:10.840
and be brutal about cutting because just getting it all in is not effective if people can't listen

00:46:10.840 --> 00:46:13.639
to it. So those are the kind of the two subset categories.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:22.280
Thank you. So while we just talked about a tool, I remember there was an anonymous question that was,

00:46:22.760 --> 00:46:29.239
do you have a favorite tool that you use to ignite creativity when planning a presentation?

00:46:33.080 --> 00:46:38.439
That's a really good question. And I don't, I mean, I don't know that we do. We often,

00:46:40.360 --> 00:46:44.040
people often come to us with an idea about what they want

00:46:44.040 --> 00:46:49.639
to include in their presentations. And, or there's a theme for a group of speakers or

00:46:49.639 --> 00:46:59.000
something like that. And so we don't often have to do that. Now, there are times when we have to

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:08.360
coax ideas out of people, but we tend to ask questions to do that instead of using a tool.

00:47:08.360 --> 00:47:13.479
I mean, I guess there's an easy, like we could say, we can put it into AI. We can put it into

00:47:13.479 --> 00:47:19.800
chat GPT and say, what would you talk about for this? And it just, it depends on your comfort

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:25.479
level with that. And you all have probably different tools that you use for AI and to

00:47:25.479 --> 00:47:31.399
kick back information like that. But we're just, one of our jobs is asking the questions to get to

00:47:31.399 --> 00:47:37.080
something, a topic that people are really excited to talk about if they haven't gotten there already.

00:47:37.800 --> 00:47:44.520
Thank you. You could also, I'll just add there, if anybody has tools that they use, I saw like Ted put

00:47:44.520 --> 00:47:48.679
mind mapping as a thing, Mila notes. So some people have tools, put them in the chat.

00:47:49.479 --> 00:47:55.080
I will also encourage people to lean into the fact that speaking is social. And it is sometimes

00:47:55.080 --> 00:48:00.679
just the act of talking about it with someone that can help you to clarify your thinking. If it's

00:48:00.679 --> 00:48:05.639
going to be spoken that you give later, then talking it out can be a great tool that I think

00:48:05.719 --> 00:48:10.199
people don't always lean on. And frankly, that's part of what gives me a job. So,

00:48:10.199 --> 00:48:14.679
people get a lot of ideas because we coach in a social manner.

00:48:17.639 --> 00:48:22.360
One thing that came up from one of our people riding on the train that felt like they couldn't

00:48:22.360 --> 00:48:28.840
ask was how has Zoom changed how you all coach on presentations or you give presentations?

00:48:28.840 --> 00:48:32.840
Is Zoom different than real life? Do you find it hard switching between the two?

00:48:32.919 --> 00:48:38.919
What do you do differently? Yeah, and I think Nitesh asked a similar question to this too.

00:48:38.919 --> 00:48:41.159
I think that was the one. I couldn't remember the name. Thank you.

00:48:43.239 --> 00:48:48.040
I think it's always been true. There's this funny little graphic that we used to show when we were

00:48:48.040 --> 00:48:57.239
helping people transition to virtual presentations. And it's this graph where on the y-axis is

00:48:58.040 --> 00:49:06.439
interest that people have and the x-axis is length of time speaking. And of course,

00:49:06.439 --> 00:49:11.800
at the beginning, people have high interest and then it loops down pretty fast to low interest

00:49:11.800 --> 00:49:17.479
as you continue speaking. And I feel like virtual, the biggest difference is that curve is steeper

00:49:17.479 --> 00:49:27.879
for most listeners. So your need to be clearer, more concise, and be able to tell people where

00:49:27.879 --> 00:49:34.919
you're going very early is much higher in a virtual world. So it takes more effort.

00:49:35.800 --> 00:49:39.320
People are more forgiving in an in-person environment because they have a lot of other

00:49:39.320 --> 00:49:44.439
stuff that helps them to come to understanding all the non-verbals, just the energy that's there.

00:49:45.399 --> 00:49:51.000
So I think the time thing and being more concise would be the biggest. Anything you would add,

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:56.280
Bly? Yeah, go ahead, J.D. I was going to say the first time I presented in a Zoom meeting where I

00:49:56.280 --> 00:50:00.919
couldn't see anyone's face. So at least here I can see five people. I presented in one where I could

00:50:00.919 --> 00:50:07.399
see nothing. It was an absolute mind melter. I found it was so hard because I was getting no

00:50:07.399 --> 00:50:13.159
facial expression feedback. And I didn't know prior to that, that I was incredibly dependent

00:50:13.159 --> 00:50:19.879
on that. And I spent that whole thing, part of my head screaming, this is awful. This something

00:50:19.879 --> 00:50:24.280
is going terribly wrong because of the lack of facial expressions. Now I watched the recording

00:50:24.280 --> 00:50:32.040
of it later and it was fine, but I found that incredibly hard. Yeah, you make a really good

00:50:32.040 --> 00:50:37.399
point. And it depends again on your culture, on your company's culture, how you're presenting,

00:50:37.399 --> 00:50:42.760
but you can ask people to come on camera. It is a pretty big requirement of Acacia's

00:50:42.760 --> 00:50:48.840
and my work that we are able to see the person we're talking to. And so I had a group of

00:50:50.679 --> 00:50:57.639
from one company that were not on camera people. And I said, I'm going to need you to come on

00:50:57.639 --> 00:51:04.280
camera. And they bristled at it, but they did it. And it enriched the experience because then

00:51:04.280 --> 00:51:09.399
you're not staring into the void. The other thing, and this is a really weird thing, and I haven't

00:51:09.399 --> 00:51:14.520
done it once yet during this Hangout, is as a speaker, and this is really hard, you want to be

00:51:14.520 --> 00:51:18.760
looking at their faces and you should just to get their reaction, but you also want to be looking

00:51:18.760 --> 00:51:23.000
into the camera so that they feel like you're making eye contact with them as well. And that's

00:51:23.000 --> 00:51:29.800
just one tiny little shift that you can make that can sometimes close the distance. When Vicky

00:51:29.800 --> 00:51:37.639
Boykis did the thing she called NormConf, she broadcasted over YouTube live. So lots of people

00:51:37.639 --> 00:51:44.840
were on YouTube. So obviously they weren't there in the room with you, but the two hosts were. And

00:51:44.840 --> 00:51:50.280
I found that was more than enough to like fill that part of my brain that needed human reaction.

00:51:50.280 --> 00:51:56.040
And what I tend to do is I know where my camera's right here, right? So I shrink the window up until

00:51:56.040 --> 00:52:00.919
the people I'm talking to are right below that camera. So I can watch them and it's right at

00:52:00.919 --> 00:52:05.879
the camera. I mean, I could move the window. So, you know, it's over here, but that's weird as hell

00:52:05.879 --> 00:52:10.120
to be talking, looking at you guys in the eye, but you're over here, right? So I put you guys

00:52:10.120 --> 00:52:14.199
right up against the camera so that when I'm looking at you, I'm looking at the camera and

00:52:14.199 --> 00:52:20.919
that's my like one hack for the virtual host. I usually have to put the main speaker, like the

00:52:20.919 --> 00:52:28.280
biggest person covering the full screen, or else I get so distracted by just like wanting to check

00:52:28.280 --> 00:52:31.800
if like someone meant to raise their hand or wanted to talk, or it looks like they were going

00:52:31.800 --> 00:52:38.199
to say something. And I just am like looking all over the place. But I know Nitesh, this was your

00:52:38.199 --> 00:52:42.120
question originally. And so I just wanted to make sure, did you have any follow-up? Because I saw

00:52:42.120 --> 00:52:46.679
you said something about like going back and forth between in-person and Zoom too.

00:52:50.919 --> 00:52:54.840
Oh, you said no, that's great. Okay. Because that's something that I was just talking about

00:52:54.840 --> 00:53:03.320
yesterday when I was in the office in Boston. So if I'm like jumping from an in-person

00:53:03.879 --> 00:53:08.840
meeting and talking to someone face-to-face, and then I go on Zoom, like something's happening

00:53:08.840 --> 00:53:13.639
to me where it's like very hard for me to do that. And I was wondering like,

00:53:14.919 --> 00:53:20.120
how do you go jump between these two different formats?

00:53:21.080 --> 00:53:27.080
You know, when we first started like doing a lot more on Zoom, we actually always worked on Zoom

00:53:27.800 --> 00:53:32.679
even before the pandemic. We did a lot of coaching with people on Zoom. So I went in thinking I kind

00:53:32.679 --> 00:53:38.360
of knew a lot. And then early in the pandemic when everything was on Zoom, I was really noticing like

00:53:38.360 --> 00:53:46.199
I was putting so much effort forth when I was on a Zoom call. And I've since been able to notice

00:53:47.159 --> 00:53:51.879
what you're talking about, Rachel, which is that when I'm in person, I'm almost unaware of how I'm

00:53:51.879 --> 00:54:00.840
using my energy because it is more innately natural to me to be in person. And then I get on

00:54:00.840 --> 00:54:08.919
virtual and I need to spend a little more time kind of grounding myself again. So for me, physical

00:54:08.919 --> 00:54:14.439
helps. Breathing is one way I've talked about, but physical also helps. So sometimes I'll just like

00:54:14.439 --> 00:54:20.600
notice the back of my chair and notice my butt in the chair so that I'm actually here.

00:54:21.639 --> 00:54:25.959
Or I'll remember, and I can even look right now at my screen and see, oh my gosh, yeah,

00:54:25.959 --> 00:54:31.479
there's a lot of space behind me. There's a whole room. I'm three-dimensional, not two-dimensional.

00:54:32.199 --> 00:54:36.040
And then I'll look at the other person and I'll imagine even right now looking at you, Rachel,

00:54:36.040 --> 00:54:40.520
you have a virtual background, but I can imagine that there's distance between you and the wall

00:54:40.520 --> 00:54:45.879
and you're three-dimensional. And these kind of tricks can help get us back inside our body

00:54:47.080 --> 00:54:51.000
so that we don't have like the out-of-body experience, which is my experience of sometimes

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:55.399
when I'm not ready to go back to Zoom is I'm not myself in those moments.

00:54:57.879 --> 00:55:04.840
Thank you. Yeah, that's really helpful. Natalia, I see you asked a question a little bit earlier.

00:55:04.840 --> 00:55:07.959
I didn't have a chance to actually like read it all at the same time,

00:55:09.639 --> 00:55:14.679
but I think it's like touching on when someone's giving advice who's not an expert in the area.

00:55:14.679 --> 00:55:20.919
Do you want to jump in? Yeah, sure. And I kind of got the answer in the chat, but yeah,

00:55:20.919 --> 00:55:26.760
if there are any additional thoughts on, I know this articulation does a lot of work with a lot

00:55:26.760 --> 00:55:33.560
of different industries and therefore presentation themes can vary. So I was curious how to approach

00:55:33.800 --> 00:55:38.919
coaching people when you're not an expert in a certain area. However, you're expert in speaking,

00:55:38.919 --> 00:55:44.919
which gives you a lot, but you have to kind of guide people in their presentation to like what

00:55:44.919 --> 00:55:50.919
to add and remove or pivot the story. So yeah, I was just fascinated in how they approach

00:55:51.800 --> 00:55:57.320
coaching for programming topics, especially like heavily technical programming topics

00:55:57.320 --> 00:56:03.959
without even being programmers. So yep, that's the question. I'm so glad you brought this up

00:56:03.959 --> 00:56:09.159
because it comes to that idea of speaking requires feedback. So it's kind of a great place to start

00:56:09.159 --> 00:56:14.679
to wind us towards the end. And if you are in the position, Natalia, like it sounds like you are to

00:56:14.679 --> 00:56:21.560
sometimes give feedback, the thing that helps to ground you no matter like how much you know about

00:56:21.560 --> 00:56:26.679
the topic is to try and keep two things really crystal clear in your mind. And this is what

00:56:26.679 --> 00:56:33.320
Blythe and I are doing. Even if we don't know the topic, we're trying to remember two things. One,

00:56:33.320 --> 00:56:41.239
who's the audience? And we try to have our biggest open idea of like, what do we think that audience

00:56:41.239 --> 00:56:47.000
wants? Now we can't know 100%, but we try to do our research. We try to make sure we're always

00:56:47.000 --> 00:56:52.360
listening like an audience member would listen. So that you're not just learning to deliver a talk

00:56:52.360 --> 00:56:56.679
that Acacia likes or Blythe likes. You're learning to deliver a talk that actually the

00:56:56.679 --> 00:57:03.719
POSIT audience is going to like. So keep in mind the audience and then always keep in mind the goal

00:57:03.719 --> 00:57:11.560
of the speaker. Because when you're giving feedback, sometimes your own wants, especially the closer

00:57:11.560 --> 00:57:18.600
you are to the material, your own desire of what you want to convey might start to color your

00:57:18.600 --> 00:57:24.679
feedback. And this can be useful in business. Like if you're the leader and you need to make

00:57:24.679 --> 00:57:28.040
sure that they have a different goal because they have the wrong goal, that's worth discussing.

00:57:28.600 --> 00:57:33.320
But I think it just always helps to keep in mind those two things. What's the audience need

00:57:33.320 --> 00:57:34.760
and what's the goal of the speaker?

00:57:37.719 --> 00:57:44.120
I think this touches on one. There's one last Slido question I think kind of goes along with

00:57:44.120 --> 00:57:50.199
this so we can fit it into the two minutes. But it was, do you have any tips on how to be yourself

00:57:50.199 --> 00:57:51.080
when presenting?

00:57:53.959 --> 00:58:00.040
So this is where the stress can sometimes get in the way. But I think I read somebody wrote

00:58:00.040 --> 00:58:06.760
something like, I used to have a boss who put on a presentation voice. And that's not a great idea.

00:58:06.760 --> 00:58:10.360
I used to have a lot of friends who would put on Shakespeare voices to present Shakespeare. And I

00:58:10.360 --> 00:58:14.600
was like, we can all just sound like humans when we do. We don't have to sound a specific way.

00:58:15.479 --> 00:58:23.479
So it sounds stupid. It sounds pat, but breathing, identifying your stress behaviors, getting ahead

00:58:23.479 --> 00:58:30.040
of them, those sorts of things. I was recently on a Posit coaching call with Joe Chang,

00:58:30.040 --> 00:58:37.080
and there was someone who was reading their talk. And Joe said, one of the things I love about Posit

00:58:37.080 --> 00:58:42.840
is that people make mistakes. And sometimes you'll stumble over your words, but it sounds

00:58:42.840 --> 00:58:49.080
natural. And that's what he was really looking for in Posit conf talks. And that's what Acacia and I

00:58:49.080 --> 00:58:56.280
are almost always looking for. So I think there's a little bit of fear about, well, if I put on this

00:58:56.280 --> 00:59:01.479
character, it's not me and I don't have to worry about it as much because it doesn't reflect on me

00:59:01.479 --> 00:59:09.959
in this particular way. But I do think that if you acknowledge the risk and you do everything you

00:59:09.959 --> 00:59:15.080
can to mitigate it, which is part of the threshold concepts, if you do everything you can to mitigate

00:59:15.080 --> 00:59:18.919
it, go in prepared, know your structure, know what question you're answering, know what your

00:59:18.919 --> 00:59:23.719
audience wants, know what your goal is. All of those things are going to help you slide into

00:59:24.360 --> 00:59:30.520
being you. And also I'm going to ask everyone to do this. Trust your knowledge. Most of the time

00:59:30.520 --> 00:59:35.719
you are there and asked to speak on something because you are a subject matter expert. So trust

00:59:35.719 --> 00:59:41.320
your innate, not your innate knowledge, but your learned knowledge. And that is going to be better

00:59:41.320 --> 00:59:48.520
than anything you could memorize or plan down to the last second in detail. Just please trust

00:59:48.520 --> 00:59:56.520
yourselves a little bit. I will only tack on one thing, which is we want to hear your voice. And by

00:59:56.520 --> 01:00:02.199
we, I mean every single audience member you ever have wants to hear your perspective. They want to

01:00:02.199 --> 01:00:08.280
hear your authentic voice. So keep that in mind as you're trying your best to do that.

01:00:10.679 --> 01:00:17.239
Thank you both so much. This has been so fun. I love this conversation today and I'm so excited

01:00:17.239 --> 01:00:22.120
to also get to go read back through some of the conversation in the chat too. Thank you all for

01:00:22.120 --> 01:00:29.239
taking the time to join us today too. If it was your first Hangout today, we'd love to have you

01:00:29.239 --> 01:00:35.959
back. Again, we have these every Thursday at the same time, same place, except for next week because

01:00:35.959 --> 01:00:42.760
we will be at the POSIT conference. But thank you all so much. And Blythe and Acacia, I really

01:00:42.760 --> 01:00:48.679
appreciate you jumping on here with us. It's great to talk about our favorite subject. So you got us

01:00:48.679 --> 01:00:53.080
on our favorite subject and with such a great group of people. We love the POSIT audience every year.

01:00:53.080 --> 01:00:59.399
It's a wonderful community. It makes me want to learn R just so I can join the community.

01:01:00.679 --> 01:01:03.959
And if you didn't get your questions asked here and you're going to be at POSITConf, find me in

01:01:03.959 --> 01:01:10.600
the hallways. I'm looking forward to seeing you. Thank you all. Have a great rest of the day, everybody.

01:01:18.679 --> 01:01:19.179
Bye.

